definition.value: A monohydroxybenzoic acid having the hydroxy group at the 4-position together with a geranyl group at the 3-position.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-4-(trimethylammonio)but-2-enoic acid.
A pyrrolopyrimidine that is 7-deazaguanine bearing a carboxylic acid substituent at the 7 position.
A 5,6,7,8-tetrahydropterin having a carboxy group at the 6-position.
Molybdopterin cytosine dinucleotide with coordinated molybdenum.
A W-molybdopterin cofactor comprising two molecules of molybdopterin guanine dinucleotide attached via their sulfur atoms to a central oxo-tungsten group.
An N-hydroxyamino acid that is derived from L-isoleucine.

An organonitrogen heterocyclic compound that is aconitane bearing hydroxy groups at the 1alpha, 8, and 14alpha positions and substituted at on the nitrogen and at positions 4 and 16beta by ethyl, methyl, and methoxy groups, respectively.
A hydroxy-amino acid in which one of the hydrogens of L-isoleucine has been substituted by a hydroxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion, obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N-hydroxy-L-isoleucine.
An N,N-dihydroxy amino acid that is derived from L-isoleucine.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino-acid anion resulting from removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N,N-dihydroxy-L-isoleucine.
An aldoxime derived from 2-methylbutanal.
A 2-methylbutanal oxime in which the oxime double bond has E geometry.
A 2-methylbutanal oxime in which the oxime double bond has Z geometry.
A hydroperoxide having the skeleton M-OOH, in which M is any metal.
An N-hydroxyamino acid that is derived from L-valine.
A hydroxy-amino acid in which one of the hydrogens of L-valine has been substituted by a hydroxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion, obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N-hydroxy-L-valine.
An N,N-dihydroxy amino acid that is derived from L-valine.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino-acid anion resulting from removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of N,N-dihydroxy-L-valine.
A 2-methylpropanal oxime in which the oxime double bond has E geometry.
A 2-methylpropanal oxime in which the oxime double bond has Z geometry.
An organophosphate oxoanion that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of 4-nitrophenyl phosphate.
A ferroheme having four carboxy groups and oxo groups on two of the pyrrole rings.
A sesquiterpenoid primary alcohol, being methanol in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 2,5,5,8a-tetramethyl-1,4,4a,5,6,7,8,8a-octahydronaphthalen-1-yl group.
An oxo carboxylic acid that is the 2,3-dihydro-3-oxo tautomer of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid.

A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is 2,3-dihydro-3-oxo tautomer of 3-hydroxyanthranilate and results from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 2,3-dihydro-3-oxoanthranilic acid.
A biomacromolecule that is composed of ADP-D-ribose units linked through glycosidic ribose-ribose 1''->2' bonds. Branching may also occur.
A carboxylic ester-lactam secreted by Mycobacterium tuberculosis which is both lipid- and water-soluble and acts as a siderophore.
The ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of clenbuterol, formed by protonation of the secondary amine nitrogen atom.
A polyprenylhydroquinone consisting of hydroquinone in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a (2Z)-3-(hydroxymethyl)-7-methylocta-2,6-dien-1-yl group.
An octadecadienoic acid having a system of two conjugated double bonds at any position.

A pyranone that is 2H-pyran-2-one substituted by a methoxy group at position 4 and a 3-phenyloxiran-2-yl group at position 6 (the 2R,3S stereoisomer). Isolated from Didymocarpus aurantiacus and Piper rusbyi, it exhibits antileishmanial activity.
Any n-3 (alpha) or n-6 (gamma)  octadecatrienoic acid in which at least two of the three double bonds are conjugated.
A polyester macromolecule composed of repeating 3-hydroxycarboxylic acid units.
A D-alanyl ester that results from the formal condensation of the alcoholic hydroxy group of (2R)-lactic acid with the carboxylic acid group of D-alanine.
Any alpha-amino acid ester that results from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of L-alanine with an alcohol.
Any alpha-amino acid ester that results from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of D-alanine with an alcohol.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxylic acid group to the amino group of D-alanyl-(R)-lactic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
An iron coordination entity being a complex of desferriexochelin 772SM with iron(3+).
A cyclic hydroxamic acid secreted by Mycobacterium tuberculosis which is lipid-soluble and acts as a siderophore.
A trimeric branched amino oligosaccharide consisting of three repeating units of beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc joined by (1->3)-linkages.
An ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of metoclopramide.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-glucosamine at the reducing end with an alpha-fucosyl-(1->2)-alpha-fucosyl group attached at the 3-position and an N-acetyl-beta-glucosaminyl residue attached at the 4-position.
An ammonium ion that is obtained by protonation of both the tertiary amino group and the anilino nitrogen of metoclopramide.

A branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of an alpha-D-Gal residue at the reducing end having an alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)-beta-D-GalNAc-(1->4)-[alpha-L-Fuc-(1->3)]-beta-D-GlcNAc moiety attached at the 3-position.
